<emphasis box="[1038,1266,1285,1309]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Afrasura dubitabilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Durante" box="[1274,1436,1285,1309]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" refString="Durante, A. (2009) Revision of the Afrotropical species of Asura Walker, 1854 (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae, Lithosiinae), with the description of a new genus. Zootaxa, 2280, 27 - 52." type="journal article" year="2009">
Durante, 
<number box="[1380,1436,1285,1309]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker, 1864" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1864" box="[204,608,1321,1345]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Afrasura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliterata">
<emphasis box="[204,424,1321,1345]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Afrasura obliterata</emphasis>
(Walker, 
<number box="[540,600,1321,1345]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="1864.0">1864</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but differing from the first in the absence of the sclerotizations in the corpus bursae at the appendix level (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Durante" box="[606,763,1357,1381]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" refString="Durante, A. (2009) Revision of the Afrotropical species of Asura Walker, 1854 (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae, Lithosiinae), with the description of a new genus. Zootaxa, 2280, 27 - 52." type="journal article" year="2009">
Durante 
<number box="[703,763,1357,1381]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and from the latter in the lack of sclerotized bundles of the ductus bursae of 
<taxonomicName box="[344,454,1393,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Afrasura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliterata">
<emphasis box="[344,454,1393,1417]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">obliterata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ending anteriorly in a tree-like shape (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Durante" box="[935,1094,1393,1417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" refString="Durante, A. (2009) Revision of the Afrotropical species of Asura Walker, 1854 (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae, Lithosiinae), with the description of a new genus. Zootaxa, 2280, 27 - 52." type="journal article" year="2009">
Durante 
<number box="[1033,1094,1393,1417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Seventh sternum sclerotized, two times longer than the sixth segment, divided longitudinally into two shields; its caudal margin with a shallow cavity in the middle. Seventh tergum membranous squared. At A 
<number box="[906,919,1466,1490]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="7.0">7</number>
pleural level two small pouches are present. Dorsal pheromone glands a little longer than posterior apophyses. Ostium bursae not strongly delimited, with roughly a U-shaped notch in the middle both dorsally and ventrally. Antrum sclerotized, cylindrical, as long as wide, internally sprinkled by microscopic spines. The ductus bursae is considered practically absent or reduced just to the membranous junction of the antrum to the cervix bursae. This is sub-conical, membranous, with a finger-like appendix from which the ductus seminalis arises. At the junction between cervix and appendix there is a small heart-shaped sclerotization with small thorns (
<figureCitation box="[669,753,1681,1705]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 39" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1273,1296]" captionTargetBox="[216,1365,206,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[196,1390,176,1270]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 39. Female genitalia of Afrasura. Images not all in proportion. 34. Afrasura emma Ƥ g. prep. 639 MAD: genitalia, bursa copulatrix in dorsal view. AP: appendix; CX: cervix; SI: signum. 35. Afrasura emma Ƥ g. prep. 639 MAD: antrum and cervix bursae enlarged. AN: antrum; AP: appendix; CX: cervix. 36. Afrasura trunca sp. n. Ƥ g. prep. 668 MAD: genitalia, bursa copulatrix in dorsal view. AN: antrum; AP: appendix; DB: ductus bursae; LP: lamella postvaginalis; SI: signum. 37. Afrasura camilla sp. n. Ƥ g. prep. 530 MAD: genitalia, in dorsal view. AN: antrum; AP: appendix; DB: ductus bursae. 38. Afrasura duplex sp. n. Ƥ g. prep. 689 MAD: genitalia, bursa copulatrix in dorsal view. AN: antrum; AP: appendix; CX: cervix. 39. Afrasura aetheria sp. n. Ƥ g. prep. 680 MAD: genitalia, bursa copulatrix in dorsal view. AP: appendix; CX: cervix." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210419/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
Fig. 
<number box="[722,753,1681,1705]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" value="35.0">35</number>
</figureCitation>
). Corpus bursae globular, membranous and strong, internally scattered by tiny thorns. Signum dimple-shaped, ovoidal, covered by minuscule spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="386" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1105,1957]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1754,1778]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described from two males from 
<collectingCountry box="[912,996,1753,1777]" name="Nigeria" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
and was differentiated by the closest species mainly by the absence of the large cornutus in the vesica, which is widespread in 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1287,1789,1813]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Afrasura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1187,1287,1789,1813]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Afrasura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. The Gabonese males show the same wingspan as the 
<typeStatus box="[707,805,1825,1849]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<quantity box="[822,904,1825,1849]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
) except two are larger (
<quantity box="[1174,1258,1825,1849]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" unit="mm" value="18.0">18 mm</quantity>
); they present a general aspect and colour similar to the Nigerian specimens (see original description in 
